    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-07-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-07-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="233"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d233">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWERGADD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName
                        corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName> papers</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by <persName corresp="#p_OCRL1" type="from">Roderic
                            L. O’Connor</persName>, Special Assistant to the Secretary of State, to
                        the Consultant for Atomic Energy Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_SMITHGC1"
                            type="to">Smith</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-07-15">July 15,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>On July 12 the President spoke to the Secretary and said that we should get busy
                    on his (the President) December 8 plan without waiting for Russia.</p>
                <p>The Secretary later called Admiral <persName corresp="#p_STRAUSSLL1"
                        >Strauss</persName> to report this. <persName corresp="#p_STRAUSSLL1"
                        >Strauss</persName> said that he was glad to hear that. The bill would be
                    reported out Wednesday, July 14, and <persName corresp="#p_STRAUSSLL1"
                        >Strauss</persName> said he thought it would pass in 3–4 days.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d233fn1">The Atomic Energy Act of 1954 was not approved by Congress
                        until Aug. 16. See the editorial note, <ref target="#pg_1505">p.
                        1505</ref>.</note> When this happened, <persName corresp="#p_STRAUSSLL1"
                        >Strauss</persName> said he would work out some conferences—the first would
                    be with Belgium. The Secretary stated that he was in favor of this. Admiral
                        <persName corresp="#p_STRAUSSLL1">Strauss</persName> said that he would let
                    the President know the above information. He said there may be a public
                    announcement as soon as he, <persName corresp="#p_STRAUSSLL1"
                    >Strauss</persName>, gets the legislative authority.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_OCRL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Roderic L. O’Connor</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
